<br>
About the fungi being level restricted I think it's effect needs to be 45 like every other Kunark drop.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
Actually, I've been playing casters since slightly before Kunark came out.  My only melee Alt is a monk who is languishing at level 29.  The rest of my characters are all 4 caster types, a bard, a cleric and a shaman.  All except the Monk are &gt;30, with my wizard being my highest I've ever managed to grind at 52 and 1AA.  Now that I've properly displayed my genetalia for public viewing, lets see some constructive conversation, thanks...<br>
<br>
I'm aware that those that have been playing longer than me had it a bit harder in the very beginning<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(I am led to believe that those playing since release had to walk uphill in the snow barefoot to reach the keyboard, and that the beta people actually had to cut themselves when a mob hit their character for immersive realism)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, However, it is ludicrious that it takes 10+ minutes to med from to full from empty at any level above about 8--- and I was saying the exact same thing when I had to stare at the stupid book till 35.<br>
<br>
I'll make this point again, because I feel it's important:<br>
----I don't play a game so that I have time to do the dishes, wash laundry, fix my car, read a novel or watch TV.  I don't want to play a game where my 'up' playing time is about 15%-50%.  <br>
<br>
KEI helped alleviate that, and due to the regenerative nature of the spell, also provided enough extra mana in combat to do things that would not ordinarily be possible without it--but not greatly so.  <br>
<br>
My personal take on this is that they <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>should</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> go ahead and make KEI only hit 45+, but make low grade Flowing thought available from level 1 on, allow it to stack higher than 15, add some kind of mana potion and give someone <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(not chanters, or not *just* chanters)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> some short duration huge mana regen spells that cancel if you cast a detrimental spell or are struck in combat.  You should not have so much mana regen you can't run out of it, but you should not have to wait more than a minute or 2 to get it back either.<br>
<br>
Apparentyly the competition realized this too-- Both DAOC and AO have ways around excessive downtime between fights.  In DAOC you regen MUCH faster out of combat <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(and out of combat is determined much better than in EQ)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, in AO you have both Healing and Mana<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(called Nano there)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> kits that will fill you up in a matter of seconds outside of a fight--Making the dependance on healers refreshingly much less for xp though they do retain their role during harder and/or larger combats.  Both games still have a healthy  player market for Mana and Health regen spells, and those who cast them are still desired in groups, the only thing missing is the utter dependance on them.  While I left DAOC for lack of content, I find AO to be a much better game in nearly every respect but their laggy network issues, and have nearly completly severed the EQ ubilical after all my time in EQ.  It hurts to leave EQ, but it's just not so fun anymore, and AO is.  Downtime is 70% of why. <p><br>
